Both ends of the canoe are sharp alike, and either serves for poop or prow, as seems good. When the river is stormi- est, they trust themselves and their families, without fear, to its waves. If ever the boat is upset by an unusually strong wave, which hap- pens but seldom‚ the Payagua gets astride the boat, and thus pursues his way. They plunge into the lowest depths of the water, and after remaining under a surprising time, emerge at an immense distance, loaden with fish.
